{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17611353","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17611353"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:09:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:09:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16208"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16208","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16208"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.62,0.11,0.11,0.03,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8899"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72920"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8899","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8899"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16208"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58390"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"6712"},{"type":"tags","id":"7017"},{"type":"tags","id":"8111"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21176"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21177"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72920","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72920"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe breast has three main groups of lymph nodes that are important in the spread of breast cancer: axillary, internal mammary, and supraclavicular nodes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the typical clinical palpability of these lymph node groups?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Axillary nodes mostly palpable, internal mammary nodes impalpable, supraclavicular nodes may be palpable","Axillary nodes mostly palpable, internal mammary nodes mostly palpable, supraclavicular nodes may be palpable","Axillary nodes impalpable, internal mammary nodes impalpable, supraclavicular nodes may be palpable","Axillary nodes impalpable, internal mammary nodes impalpable, supraclavicular nodes impalpable","Axillary nodes mostly palpable, internal mammary nodes impalpable, supraclavicular nodes impalpable"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eaxillary nodes are mostly palpable\u003C/strong\u003E on clinical examination due to their relatively superficial location. These nodes receive approximately 75% of breast lymphatic drainage and are a common site of breast cancer metastasis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Einternal mammary nodes are impalpable\u003C/strong\u003E because they lie deep within the chest wall along the internal thoracic vessels. Despite being impalpable, they are an important route of lymphatic spread, particularly from medial breast lesions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esupraclavicular nodes may be palpable\u003C/strong\u003E when enlarged, which often indicates advanced disease in breast cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe remaining options suggesting that \u003Cstrong\u003Eaxillary nodes are impalpable\u003C/strong\u003E or that \u003Cstrong\u003Einternal mammary nodes are mostly palpable\u003C/strong\u003E are incorrect based on anatomical location and clinical examination findings.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The axillary lymph nodes are palpable on clinical examination.","Internal mammary lymph nodes are not palpable due to their location deep within the chest wall.","Supraclavicular lymph nodes may be palpable when enlarged, indicating advanced disease in breast cancer."],"references":["Estourgie SH, Nieweg OE, Olmos RA, Rutgers EJ, Kroon BB. Lymphatic drainage patterns from the breast. Ann Surg. 2004 Feb;239(2):232-7. doi: 10.1097/01.sla.0000109156.26378.90. PMID: 14745331; PMCID: PMC1356216.","Rao R, Euhus D, Mayo HG, Balch C. Axillary node interventions in breast cancer: a systematic review. JAMA. 2013 Oct 2;310(13):1385-94. doi: 10.1001/jama.2013.277804. PMID: 24084924.","Ezzo J, Manheimer E, McNeely ML, Howell DM, Weiss R, Johansson KI, Bao T, Bily L, Tuppo CM, Williams AF, Karadibak D. Manual lymphatic drainage for lymphedema following breast cancer treatment. Cochrane Database Syst Rev. 2015 May 21;2015(5):CD003475. doi: 10.1002/14651858.CD003475.pub2. PMID: 25994425; PMCID: PMC4966288.","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58390"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16208"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58390","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58390"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-22T17:52:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T15:52:23+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8899"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72920"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group